2.1 Students simulate round-robin and priority scheduling using sample process queues.


2.2 Students write simple programs to create child processes and terminate them.


2.3 Students draw diagrams showing how threads share resources within a process.

2.4 Students list real-world applications that benefit from multithreading (e.g., web servers, GUIs).


2.5 Students implement a simple program using thread pools and fork-join in Python or Java.


2.6 Students use system tools (Process Explorer in Windows, htop in Linux) to observe thread representation.


2.7 Students calculate turnaround time, waiting time, and CPU utilization for sample process sets under different algorithms.


2.8 Students simulate real-time task scheduling using sample task sets with deadlines.